<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-11-30T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-11-30T15:00:00-05:00" n="361" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d361">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72119/953</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-11-30T15:00:00-05:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">November 30, 1917, 3 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>5930. Your 7782.<note n="1" xml:id="d361fn1">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_317">p.
                                    317</ref>.</note> For your information. The conclusion of a
                                separate peace with Turkey is regarded as chimerical and of
                                questionable advantage even if it could be accomplished. At the
                                conference which closes the war arrangements must be made with
                                regard to Constantinople which could not be made if peace were first
                                declared with Turkey. At the present time separate peace could only
                                be made which would preclude any radical changes of control over
                                Constantinople and the Straits. It appears, therefore, to this
                                Government that the only advantage to be gained by separate peace
                                with Turkey now would be to prevent the bargains of the Allies with
                                regard to Asia Minor from being carried out at the end of the
                                war.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>